The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Spanco holding to cost RCL Rs 32 cr

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Mumbai, Aug. 23: Reliance Capital Ltd seems to be on the prowl.

 The Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Enterprises (ADAE) flagship today confirmed that it would pick up a 14.96 per cent stake in Spanco Telesystems amp; Solutions Ltd for Rs 32.27 crore ? the third major acquisition since the company came under Anil Ambanis fold after the amicable partition of the Reliance empire in June. 

 Reliance Capital today said it has agreed to subscribe to 29.80 lakh equity shares and 5.70 lakh warrants of Spanco Telesystems, representing 14.96 per cent stake of the company, at a price of Rs 90.90 per share aggregating Rs 32.27 crore.

 Spanco Telesystems will issue the shares to Reliance Capital under the preferential route.

 Earlier, the ADAE group had acquired Adlabs and bought out the entire stake of AMP Sanmar Life Insurance.

 Spanco will expand its call centre business from around 2,500 seats to 6,000 seats after RCL completes the acquisition. 

 Analysts said the Spanco takeover would augur well for the ADAE group because many of its group companies, which have so far been outsourcing some of their works, might shift to Spanco. 

 The groups another telecom flagship, Reliance Infocomm, is expected to give its customer service business to Spanco, which is already doing it for two state-run telecom giants, Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited and Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited. 

 Meanwhile, ADAE today also announced the appointment of Rajesh Sawhney in Reliance Entertainment as its president.

 Rajesh will be a key member of the ADAE leadership team in the media and entertainment space, and will initially focus on launching the groups Internet and portal strategies, providing movies, entertainment and gaming content for the benefit of millions of mobile customers of Reliance Infocomm, said a company release.

 Sawhney comes to Reliance Entertainment from Times Internet Ltd, where he was the chief operating officer. Sawhney built Indiatimes.com from a start-up venture to a fast growing and profitable business for the Times group .




